{
  "doc_id": "41508",
  "text": "Although similar in the early phase of acute infection, concentrations of NO-derived metabolites rose more in C57BL/6 mice than in BALB/c mice as the disease progressed. Synthesis of NO, which plays an essential role in resistance to T. cruzi infection [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , can also be detrimental, given its role in inflammation and tissue damage [CITATION_3] . The results reported here seem to support the latter view, as judged by the disease outcome of C57BL/6 mice. Furthermore, the demonstration that NO production is stimulated by TNF-a and inhibited by IL-10 [CITATION_4] is in line with present findings.",
